<subSubSection id="C3406503937B887DFF09FD73FE69FC69" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE53688937B887DFF09FD73FE69FC69" blockId="15.[151,639,698,1729]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFF09FD73FEF2FCD3" bold="true" box="[175,280,752,773]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Species of this genus have been associated with 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D0B937B887DFEE4FC89FE11FCC9" authority="Spinola" authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1844" box="[322,507,778,799]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pelonium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFEE4FC89FE48FCC9" box="[322,418,778,799]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Pelonium</emphasis>
Spinola
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D0B937B887DFD90FC89FEC6FCEC" authority="LeConte. From" authorityName="LeConte. From" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Cregya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFD90FC89FD94FCC9" box="[566,638,778,799]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Cregya</emphasis>
LeConte. From
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D0B937B887DFE90FCA6FE7BFCEC" authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1844" box="[310,401,805,826]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pelonium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFE90FCA6FE7BFCEC" box="[310,401,805,826]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Pelonium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D0B937B887DFE07FCA6FE0DFCEC" box="[417,487,805,826]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Diutius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFE07FCA6FE0DFCEC" box="[417,487,805,826]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Diutius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens can be distinguished by having 10 antennomeres; 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D0B937B887DFF31FCD9FF19FCB9" authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1844" box="[151,243,858,879]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pelonium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFF31FCD9FF19FCB9" box="[151,243,858,879]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Pelonium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens have 11 antennomeres. The capitular antennomeres of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D0B937B887DFE04FCF7FE02FC5F" box="[418,488,884,905]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Diutius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFE04FCF7FE02FC5F" box="[418,488,884,905]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Diutius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens are long and slender, but in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D0B937B887DFE30FC0CFE31FC72" authorityName="LeConte. From" authorityYear="1861" box="[406,475,911,932]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Cregya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFE30FC0CFE31FC72" box="[406,475,911,932]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Cregya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens they are short and triangular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3406503937B887DFF09FC47FC65FC83" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE53688937B887DFF09FC47FC65FC83" blockId="15.[151,639,698,1729]" lastBlockId="15.[685,1172,194,906]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFF09FC47FE88FC0F" bold="true" box="[175,354,964,985]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 6.0–8.4 mm; width 2.2–3.0 mm. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFE89FC5CFE81FC22" bold="true" box="[303,363,991,1012]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Form</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13612A0D937B887DFE27FC5CFDFAFC22" box="[385,528,991,1012]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="12.[197,237,1672,1691]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,193,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[172,1193,193,1649]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs. 61–64. Habitus. 61) Diutius gallerucoides; 62) Diutius pallidus; 63) Akonesis vittatis; 64) Akonesis pictipennis." pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Figs. 61, 62</figureCitation>
): Oblong, robust (about 3X longer than broad), body deep. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFF31FB97FF1EFBFF" bold="true" box="[151,244,1044,1065]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Vestiture</emphasis>
: Dorsum profusely vested with pale pubescence; antenna moderately setose; elytra with 1° and no 2° setae or without 1° but with 2° setae. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFEA5FBE7FED6FBAF" bold="true" box="[259,316,1124,1145]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Head</emphasis>
: Cranium subquadrate, frons narrower or as wide as eye, profusely indented with small setiferous punctures; gula large, subquadrate, sutures diverging anteriorly, gula with 2 well-developed, setose post-gular processes; labrum shallow, incised distally; mandibles stout, anterior dens acuminate, medial and posterior dens well-developed; maxilla well-developed, terminal palpomere securiform; labium welldeveloped, terminal palpomere securiform, capitulum long and slender (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D937B887DFEC9FAEDFE5FFA55" box="[367,437,1390,1411]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[197,238,1368,1387]" captionTargetBox="[174,1163,203,1350]" captionTargetId="figure-110@6.[172,1193,183,1363]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 30–42. Morphological structures. 30) Akonesis vittatis, pronotum; 31) Akonesis pictipennis, pronotum; 32) Diutus pallidus, pronotum; 33) Crusbatus spinosus, pronotum; 34) D. pallidus, antenna; 35) Diutus gallerucoides, antenna; 36) C. spinosus, antenna; 37) D. pallidus, tegmen; 38) D. pallidus, phallus; 39) C. spinosus, spicular fork; 40) C. spinosus, male, pygidium; 41) C. spinosus, tegmen; 42) C. spinosus, phallus." pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
) eyes large, coarsely faceted, ocular notch large; antenna comprised of 10 antennomeres, capitate, capitulum long and slender, funicular antennomeres subfiliform. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFF31FA5BFF0CFA3B" bold="true" box="[151,230,1496,1517]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum slightly subquadrate, disc flat, side margins with slightly developed lateral tubercle, dorsolateral carina incomplete but extending anteriorly beyond tubercle and confluent with pronotal hem posteriorly, prointercoxal process narrow, slightly expanded distally; pronotal projections long, approximating prointercoxal process; elytron with or without asetiferous punctures, epipleural fold wide and in ventral position, tapered to elytral apex, elytral anterior margin not carinate; metathoracic wing fully developed; profemora not swollen and without spines, tibial spur formula 0-2-2, tarsal pulvillar formula 3-3-3, ungues with basal denticle. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFCB7FEC4FC96FE8A" bold="true" box="[785,892,327,348]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D937B887DFBA3FEC4FB67FE8A" box="[1029,1165,327,348]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[197,238,1368,1387]" captionTargetBox="[174,1163,203,1350]" captionTargetId="figure-110@6.[172,1193,183,1363]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 30–42. Morphological structures. 30) Akonesis vittatis, pronotum; 31) Akonesis pictipennis, pronotum; 32) Diutus pallidus, pronotum; 33) Crusbatus spinosus, pronotum; 34) D. pallidus, antenna; 35) Diutus gallerucoides, antenna; 36) C. spinosus, antenna; 37) D. pallidus, tegmen; 38) D. pallidus, phallus; 39) C. spinosus, spicular fork; 40) C. spinosus, male, pygidium; 41) C. spinosus, tegmen; 42) C. spinosus, phallus." pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Figs. 37, 38</figureCitation>
) shorter than length of abdomen, distal region of phallobase lobed, lateral lobes not fimbriate, tegmen short, phallobasic struts confluent with phallobasic apodeme, phallobasic rod absent, phallic plates wide, spinous at their outer margins; spicular fork well-developed (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D937B887DFB9AFE65FB6DFE2D" box="[1084,1159,486,507]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,215,1438,1457]" captionTargetBox="[164,1158,191,1428]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[151,1172,183,1428]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–15. Akonesis vittatis. 1) Head, frontal view; 2) Head, ventral view; 3) Head, dorsal view; 4) Pronotum; 5) Antenna; 6) Prothorax, ventral view; 7) Metathoracic wing; 8) Mandible; 9) Labium; 10) Maxilla; 11) Labrum; 12) Tegmen; 13) Phallus; 14) Metendosternite; 15) Spicular fork." pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
), spicular apodemes fused, intraspicular plate long and linear. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFCD0FD98FBA3FDE6" bold="true" box="[886,1097,539,560]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Alimentary canal</emphasis>
: With well-developed stomodaeum, ventriculus, and proctodaeum (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D937B887DFCE3FDD2FC7CFDB0" box="[837,918,593,614]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[175,215,1137,1156]" captionTargetBox="[187,1148,186,1120]" captionTargetId="figure-215@7.[151,1172,183,1133]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 43–46. Diutus pallidus. 43) Alimentary canal; 44) Male mesodermal internal reproductive system; 45) Female mesodermal internal reproductive system; 46) Brain and ventral nerve cord." pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
); ventricular crypts not well-developed; 4 cryptonephridial malpighian tubules. 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFCB6FD05FD1DFD63" bold="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Female mesodermal reproductive organs</emphasis>
: Spermathecal capsule feebly sclerotized; spermathecal gland attached to middle of capsule (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D937B887DFC81FD56FC9EFD3C" box="[807,884,725,746]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[175,215,1137,1156]" captionTargetBox="[187,1148,186,1120]" captionTargetId="figure-215@7.[151,1172,183,1133]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 43–46. Diutus pallidus. 43) Alimentary canal; 44) Male mesodermal internal reproductive system; 45) Female mesodermal internal reproductive system; 46) Brain and ventral nerve cord." pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFC2CFD56FCA3FCD3" bold="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Male mesodermal reproductive organs</emphasis>
: Two pairs of accessory glands, lateral pair much longer than medial pair; testis spheroid (
<figureCitation id="13612A0D937B887DFCBEFCA6FC80FCEC" box="[792,874,805,826]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[175,215,1137,1156]" captionTargetBox="[187,1148,186,1120]" captionTargetId="figure-215@7.[151,1172,183,1133]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 43–46. Diutus pallidus. 43) Alimentary canal; 44) Male mesodermal internal reproductive system; 45) Female mesodermal internal reproductive system; 46) Brain and ventral nerve cord." pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFC24FCA6FD03FC83" bold="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Brain and ventral nerve chord</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation id="13612A0D937B887DFC99FCC3FC61FC83" box="[831,907,832,853]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[175,215,1137,1156]" captionTargetBox="[187,1148,186,1120]" captionTargetId="figure-215@7.[151,1172,183,1133]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 43–46. Diutus pallidus. 43) Alimentary canal; 44) Male mesodermal internal reproductive system; 45) Female mesodermal internal reproductive system; 46) Brain and ventral nerve cord." pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3406503937B887DFD63FCD9FC8DFC5C" pageId="15" pageNumber="426" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BE53688937B887DFD63FCD9FC8DFC5C" blockId="15.[685,1172,194,906]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis id="B92EEA9A937B887DFD63FCD9FCA9FCB9" bold="true" box="[709,835,858,879]" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Distribution.</emphasis>
This genus is known from 
<collectingCountry id="F34D7618937B887DFBE5FCD9FB7BFCB9" box="[1091,1169,858,879]" name="Ecuador" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F34D7618937B887DFD0BFCF6FD1EFC5C" box="[685,756,885,906]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F34D7618937B887DFC81FCF6FC88FC5C" box="[807,866,885,906]" name="Brazil" pageId="15" pageNumber="426">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
